There is not a lot of information on the gun using the internet - only single barrel shotguns show up in most searches. Either the gun is extremely rare or some other markings have been worn off. What I did find:

"The Columbia double barrel shotgun was made by Simonis, Janssen & Dumoulin who were Belgium gun makers from 1884 to 1905 were sold by Henry C. Squires."

I can not attest to the accuracy of this though. There have been several Columbia named firearms companies over the last 150 years.

Overall I would say the shotgun is in pretty good condition considering its' age.

postcontent:
Sold Pending funds

First is a Hanover Arms Company side by side 12 gauge shotgun. $85.00 o.b.o.

Exposed "rabbit ears" hammers and double triggers. It was made between 1890 and 1920 in Belgium. It has 30" barrels and locks up tightly. Some pitting in the bore. The forearm is solid and also snaps in place firmly. It has a metal buttplate on the stock. The stock has a deep rich patina. There is a sliver of wood missing from the insetting of the right hammer group but it is not a functional problem. I have shot the gun. 95

Second is a Hartford Fire Arms Co. side by side 12 gauge shotgun. $85.00 o.b.o.

Exposed "rabbit ears" hammers and double triggers. Lock up is a little loose but I have shot it and it is still a functional gun. Great inexpensive security piece. With the external hammers you know if the gun is cocked and locked. Looks great on a wall as well. Great piece of history and a great conversation piece. Bore has some pitting as well, wood is heavily patinated and the steel is a little pitted in spots but uniform in color and charachter.

Wall hangers, shooters, future sawed offs or Numrich candidates. Their future is up to you.  Take them both for $150.00 Email me for extra pictures.

Sorry, I don't have the original box and papers, LOL. Look at my other ads, also. I will be selling the bulk of my collection over the next month or so to fund a large project. I will have some things for sale that will interest all different collectors and shooters.

Sales Order:

If the ad is up and I do not list it as "sale pending" then it is still for sale. Do not message me with "do you still have it" or "is it still available". I will assume you are a spam bot trying to get my email address and I will ignore you. "I am interested" is a close second that is being used also. I myself answer an ad with where I am located and when I would be available. That always gets a persons attention. I try to sell to the first person who contacts me first. After that I contact the second response and so on. This had always worked for me in the past, but as time changed and more people flaked on me or wanted me to wait beyond an agreed upon time/day, I have changed my method to a "first with the cash gets the prize". As in everything communication is king, I can't read your mind. I am not interested in Shipping a gun anywhere. If I was, I would be advertising it to a national audience auction site and asking more. Like all things, If I get enough ridiculous offers and somebody just has to have this because it reminds them of the one dear old dad used to have and has more dollars than the local's sense, I will ship to your local FFL if he will accept a direct ship gun from a private owner. Postal Money order to be cleared first. I will not sell to a low baller, I will sell through afore mentioned Auction site or just keep the item.

Disclaimers and Information:

I am not a gun shop or professional gunsmith, there is no sales tax or background fees. I do not take credit cards. I also will not accept a cashier's check, personal check, money order or anything other than CASH. If you email me a low-ball offer and say that you will pay in CASH, like it is something special and I am selling a used car, I will assume you are a effing retard who shouldn't own a gun to begin with. Contact me and I will email the best pictures I can manage. No, I am not a professional photographer. I do not look at my phone all day hoping I have email. I check it when I get home from work and occasionally on the week ends. Please don't get discouraged and think I am ignoring you if I don't return an email in 5 minutes. I am not willing to drive across the state to meet you so that you can inspect the gun and make me an offer. Driving halfway across town is a different matter all together, but I hope you will have made your offer ahead of time. If not, I may take my toys and go home. Yes, I know what the asking price on Gunbroker is, I also know what they sell for along with shipping and transfer fee and credit card fee. I do not dignify ridiculous offers with a reasonable response, they will get a ridiculous response, if any response at all. I do not NEED to sell anything, I would just LIKE to. Reasonable offers are considered, not necessarily accepted, but considered. Please do not drag the moral character of my relatives into any disagreement, I can't help it, they are like that. Mom in particular. All firearms should be considered loaded at all times, they may not be, but it is safer to consider them that way. Do not ever fire any gun if you have any doubt about it safety, functionality, or ammo/caliber match. Always consult a professional to be better safe than sorry.  Spammers and scammers beware, I have a loaded LOIC (low orbit ion cannon) and I know how to use it.

P.S.

I am sorry this is sooo long but every day somebody fails to see reason and acts outside the bounds of my endurance. Check back often as the list continues to grow, ha.
